	<tr>
		
			<td colspan="2" bgcolor="#DEDACB" background="http://www.everlore.com/gimages/tb_beige.gif">
		
				<font face="verdana" size="2" color="black">
				Let's say you're a necromancer, level 49.  You get to cast the Invoke Death spell, getting a brown skeleton pet that can kick some good butt.  But you'll notice, about half the time you cast a pet at this level, if you con it, you'll be getting a &quot;green&quot; pet.  What this means is that the result of a random number was lower in the range that it can be, and the computer uses this low number to adjust the capabilities of your pet, sometimes making him reduced in effectiveness, and conning green.  The pet simply has a lower maximum hit, and lower hitpoints.  You can cast reclaim energy on your pet, get a little bit of the mana back that made it, and try casting again until you get a blue pet.  At level 49 the pets I've seen can hit for either 47, 49, 51, 53, or 55 points maximum per hit.  The encyclopedia necrothurgia changes this.  If you assign the pet that hits for 47 the value of 1, and the pet that hits for 55 a value of five, with intermediate values in between, your random number generator will add 1 to this number if you have the encyclopedia equipped.  Just use it while you're casting the pet, you don't need it thereafter.  So what effect does this have?  Essentially a better chance at casting a tougher pet.  Your pet will always hit for at least 49 now, but the maximum will still be 55, though the chances your pet will be the one that can hit for 55 will be greater since the computer can roll a 4 or a 5 and get the result as if it rolled a 5 either way.  Make sense?<BR>
<BR>
<BR>
Proud Warlock<BR>
Of an Anonymous Guild =)
				</font>
			</td>

	</tr>
	
